    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. i think it might be nutrients though because the yellowing is mostly at the very bottom and it's spreading up a bit. how can i tell if it's nitrogen? also how do i check the soil ph to make sure the plants can actually use the fertilizer i add?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yellowing at the bottom and spreading up the stems can indicate nitrogen, but to confirm, look for a uniform yellowing over several leaf rows, suggestive of a nutrient deficiency. To test for nitrogen, you can consult a soil test kit specific for grass or compost, which can give a baseline reading. Phosphorus, potassium, calcium, and magnesium levels are provided; nitrogen and sulfur levels are only given asymptotically by such kits.\n\nFor more accurate results, send a soil sample to a professional testing service, available through your local Master Gardeners' program, cooperative extension, or commercial laboratories.\n\n\n*** Check the soil acidity or alkalinity using a soil pH testing kit or send a sample to a lab, as tomatoes prefer slightly acidic to neutral soil (pH 6.0 - 7.0). Adjust pH with sulfur (to lower it) or lime (to raise it) if necessary. Make sure to re-test the pH and nutrients after additions to your soil to avoid overcorrecting. Equipped with the accurate test results, top dressing with the appropriate soils amendments and fertilizers should help resolve the issue. Remember, visual diagnosis tools are most reliable when used judiciously alongside an understanding of the specific symptoms a",
