    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "It is possible that initially less rich soil could lead to poor nutrient availability, making it seem as though nutrients are being 'stolen.' However, soil can certainly become depleted over time from leaching, poor nutrient retention, or plant uptake, which can lead to nutrient deficiencies.\n\nLess fertile soil -- also known as low organic matter -- tends to have a narrower topsoil zone with sparse root growth, leading to more pronounced nutrient depletion. In severely depleted soils, fertilizers are required to replenish trace elements that may otherwise be lacking.\n\nTo top-dress nutrient-repleted soil, you may need to mineralize it or chemically increase its fertility. A soil scientist can assist with the entire process and soil evaluation and give suggestions if it requires amelioration, which encompasses the preparation, modification, and improvement of soil to attain optimum biological functionality after which approximate 'cultivation' or 'twisting' proceeds. This can involve the addition of compost, manure, and other organic matter to build up the fertility and the microbial activity necessary for a thriving plant biomass. This should be done in consultation with a local university's Cooperative Extension Service, or a soil laboratory.\n\nBy working with a soil scientist or an agricultural expert, you can determine the cause of the impoverished soils and",
